pr_review_comment_body:
@taliesinb Thanks for the feedback on the wording. I'll update it to be more clear. It seems like you are doing everything exactly right. Once you do a scalainstall it will install locally in your maven a new `1.3.0-SNAPSHOT`.  Since you updated your project.clj to use this, it will load up the updated jar. The `WARN` is again misleading and can be improved, but it should be working :)
As far as running just one test, you can certainly do that with `lein test :only org.apache.clojure-mxnet.ndarray-test` and `lein test :only org.apache.clojure-mxnet.operator-test`.

Thanks again for the feedback and let me know if you have any other issues

We've discussed in the past that this is not a magic preferred by the team... But in this case it's different because you're not adding any magic, it was already there. However, the current selector is really imperfect because it will fail quite dramatically for 3D grayscale images. (Note also that you are ignoring the `multichannel` argument!!!)

I see two options for this:

1. If we want to maintain this magic, which to reiterate was already there:

```python
def _multichannel_default(multichannel, ndim, last_dim):
    if multichannel is not None:
        return multichannel
    if ndim == 3 and last_dim in [3, 4]:
        return True
    else:
        return False
```

2. if we want to deprecate this behaviour and specify a new default (i.e. universally `True` or `False`), we additionally need to raise a deprecation warning when `multichannel is None`.

Setting a class default of `_initialized = False` would make this method pellucid:

```python
    def __del__(self):
        if self._initialized:
            self.close()
```

@ankurankan For x=[frm], 
the algorithm does not include lower half it only takes cdf from, frm+step/2 to frm
but for other points it takes cdf from x+step/2 to x-step/2.

This register/unregister being necessary in a test is a hint to me that the API could be improved. The ideal I would look for is the pattern of initializing an object in a fixture, and then not worrying about state from one test polluting another test. That's awkward with this global `registry` singleton.  Something like a `make_registry()` method that initializes a new registry with all the defaults would enables us to do:

```py
@pytest.fixture
def registry():
    return make_registry()
```

Then we don't have to worry about unregistering.

Since there are other more pressing issues, maybe just capture the idea into an issue and we can come back to it later. (if you like it)

Generally good to not have this have the same name as the outer function (just for naming clarity).  Also,  I think you can accomplish this without the inner function using:

```
def outer_iter():
    if thing:
        raise Exception(...)
    return (value for value in iter_something())
```

This will hit the validation step when called (as opposed to when `next` is first called.  Do you think readability seems better with that pattern?

This is too weak, this would also allow `False` or `''` or `0` as a key. Tests for `None` should better be explicit. I'd suggest the following (it does some things slightly differently):
```python
# check if the keys of the dictionary are valid
if isinstance(inputs, dict):
    for key in inputs:
        if (key is not None) and (not isinstance(key, Layer)):
            raise TypeError(... % type(key))
```

Since you're using `.set` anyways here, I'd probably just do this:


```js
const newState = Immutable.Map(action.payload.kernelspecs).map(
  (key: string, value: KernelspecProps) => makeKernelspec(value)
);
```

Plain ``assert``s get stripped from the code when byte-compiling with ``-O``, so they shouldn't be used at all. In tests you want ``np.testing.assert_`` instead, here I think something like this would be cleaner:

    if cH.shape != cV.shape:
        raise RuntimeError("Mismatch in shape of intermediate coefficient arrays")

Suggestion: Instead of adding a `if (mEnabled)` which requires the a lot of the code to shifted to right (to be inside the `if`) how about if we handle the "not enabled" case at the top of the method and do `ExitNow()`. It makes the diff smaller. Something like this:

```
if (!mEnabled) 
{
        mPendingWaitingForData   = false;
        mPendingTransmitOobFrame = false;
        mPendingActiveScan       = false;
        mPendingEnergyScan       = false;
        mPendingTransmitBeacon   = false;
        mPendingTransmitData     = false;
        mOobFrame                = NULL;
        ExitNow();
}
````

This way we also skip the log (which adds "Starting operation "<something>")  which is at the end of method when `mEnabled` is false.

Do you think it could be helpful to have a compatibility module pyDatalab? The compatibility module could contain helper function for common python 2/3 compatibility issues. For example:

```
def compat_inspect_getargspec(obj):
	if sys.version_info.major > 2:
		return obj.getfullargspec  # for python 3 compatibility
	else:
		return obj.getargspec(**kw)
```

Then we can use the compatibility functions directly:
```
    self.assertEqual(spec_fn(core_sd.analyze), compat_inspect_getargspec(core_sd.analyze_async))
    self.assertEqual(spec_fn(core_sd.analyze), compat_inspect_getargspec(core_sd._analyze))
```

class should derive from `object`:
```
class LayersConfig(object):
...
```
